    <article class="day" id="day-5">
      <header class="day-head">
        <div class="day-num-big">05</div>
        <div class="day-title-block">
          <div class="day-kicker">DAY 5 · WEEK 3</div>
          <div class="day-title">Agentic AI Foundation</div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-toggle">+</div>
      </header>
      <div class="day-body">
        <p class="day-intro">An agent loops: think → act → observe → repeat. Today you build one from scratch and learn why agents fail in production.</p>

        
      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">ReAct agent from scratch</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">ReAct = Reason + Act. The original 2022 paper that made tool-using LLMs practical. Build it once in pure Python so frameworks stop feeling like magic.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">ReAct paper plain-English summary</span>
          <span class="resource-source">arXiv (paper) + summaries</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hKVhRA9kfeM" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type video">video</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Build a ReAct agent from scratch (no framework)</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangChain YouTube</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/building-effective-agents" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Building effective AI agents</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Anthropic Engineering</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Write a ReAct loop in &lt;100 lines: parse Claude's tool-call output, execute, append result, repeat until 'final answer'. No LangChain.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Tool calling & reasoning loop</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Modern LLMs output structured tool calls (JSON). You provide a list of tools with schemas; the model picks one and fills args; you execute and return.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://docs.claude.com/en/docs/agents-and-tools/tool-use/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Anthropic Tool Use guide</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Anthropic Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/function-calling" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">OpenAI function calling</span>
          <span class="resource-source">OpenAI Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://blog.langchain.dev/tool-calling-with-langchain/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Tool calling: the complete pattern reference</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangChain Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Add 3 tools to your day-5 ReAct loop: <code>get_weather</code>, <code>calculator</code>, <code>search_notes</code>. Test: 'What's 17% of the temperature in Binghamton?'</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Memory systems for agents</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Three kinds: short-term (chat history within a session), long-term (vector store of past interactions), procedural (learned tool-use patterns). Most prod agents use short + long.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/concepts/memory/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">LangGraph memory guide</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangGraph Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.letta.com/blog/agent-memory" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Long-term memory for AI agents</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Letta Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PC9UM4l_pT4" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type video">video</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Memory patterns for agents</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangChain YouTube</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Add short-term memory to your ReAct agent (pass full chat history each call). Then add long-term: store every tool call + result in Chroma; retrieve top-3 similar past calls before each new query.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Reliability caveats in production</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Agents fail predictably: tool errors, infinite loops, hallucinated tool args, context exhaustion, vendor outages. Plan for all five from day one.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://hamel.dev/blog/posts/agents-fail/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Why most agents fail in production</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Hamel Husain</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.oreilly.com/radar/what-we-learned-from-a-year-of-building-with-llms-part-i/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">What we learned from a year of building with LLMs</span>
          <span class="resource-source">O'Reilly</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Add a max-iterations limit (10) and a try/except around every tool call to your agent. Test with a query designed to confuse it (e.g., 'use the calculator to find tomorrow's lottery numbers').</p>
        </div>
      </div>

        <div class="checkpoint">
          <span class="checkpoint-icon">✓</span>
          <span><strong>Checkpoint:</strong> Name three failure modes of agents in production and how you'd defend against each.</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="day" id="day-6">
      <header class="day-head">
        <div class="day-num-big">06</div>
        <div class="day-title-block">
          <div class="day-kicker">DAY 6 · WEEK 3</div>
          <div class="day-title">Agent Orchestration & LangGraph</div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-toggle">+</div>
      </header>
      <div class="day-body">
        <p class="day-intro">LangGraph treats agents as state machines: explicit nodes, edges, and shared state. The 2026 standard for production agents.</p>

        
      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Workflow state machines</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Each node is a function that reads/writes shared state. Edges decide where to go next. Replaces brittle while-loops with explicit control flow.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://academy.langchain.com/courses/intro-to-langgraph" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type course">course</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">LangGraph 101 (free)</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangChain Academy</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/tutorials/introduction/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">LangGraph quickstart</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangGraph Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hvAPnpSfSGo" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type video">video</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">LangGraph deep dive (Harrison Chase)</span>
          <span class="resource-source">YouTube</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Convert your day-5 ReAct agent to LangGraph: 'agent' node, 'tools' node, conditional edge between them. Same behavior, explicit graph.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Conditional branches & loops</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Conditional edges route based on state: 'if last message has tool_calls, go to tools; else END'. Loops are explicit edges that point back.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/how-tos/branching/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">LangGraph control flow patterns</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangGraph Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://blog.langchain.dev/langgraph/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">LangGraph patterns: routing, branching, HITL</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangChain Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Add a 'reviewer' node to your graph that runs after the agent generates an answer. If the reviewer says 'incomplete', loop back to the agent with feedback. Max 3 loops.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Routing, guardrails & compliance (HIPAA, GDPR)</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Production agents in regulated domains need a guardrail node that checks for PII, medical advice, or out-of-scope questions BEFORE the main agent runs.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.guardrailsai.com/docs" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Guardrails AI — open source guardrail library</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Guardrails AI</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://microsoft.github.io/presidio/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Microsoft Presidio — PII detection</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Presidio Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.anthropic.com/news/hipaa" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">HIPAA-compliant LLM systems</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Anthropic</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Add a guardrail entry node: if the query contains PII (regex for email/SSN/phone) or matches a 'medical advice' classifier prompt, route directly to END with a refusal.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Trajectory evaluations</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Evaluate the full sequence of node executions, not just the final answer. Did the agent take a sensible path? Did it call the right tools in the right order?</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://docs.smith.langchain.com/evaluation/concepts#trajectory" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">LangSmith trajectory evaluators</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangSmith Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://blog.langchain.dev/evaluating-trajectories/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Beyond final-answer eval: judging the path</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangChain Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Run 5 queries through your graph. For each, log the sequence of nodes visited. Manually score: did it take the right path? This is 'trajectory eval' done by hand.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

        <div class="checkpoint">
          <span class="checkpoint-icon">✓</span>
          <span><strong>Checkpoint:</strong> Why is an explicit state graph easier to debug than a while-loop with if-statements?</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
    </section>

    <section class="week">
      <header class="week-header">
        <div class="week-num">04</div>
        <div class="week-info">
          <div class="week-tag">Week 4</div>
          <div class="week-title">Production Plumbing<br><span class="week-sub">Tracing, deployment, evals, guardrails.</span></div>
        </div>
      </header>
      
    <article class="day" id="day-7">
      <header class="day-head">
        <div class="day-num-big">07</div>
        <div class="day-title-block">
          <div class="day-kicker">DAY 7 · WEEK 4</div>
          <div class="day-title">LangSmith & AWS Deployment</div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-toggle">+</div>
      </header>
      <div class="day-body">
        <p class="day-intro">Once your agent leaves your laptop, you need observability and a way to ship it. LangSmith + Docker + AWS is the bootcamp's path.</p>

        
      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Traces, runs & structured feedback</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">A trace is the full record of one user request: every prompt, response, tool call, latency, token count, error. Indispensable for debugging.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://docs.smith.langchain.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">LangSmith Getting Started</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangSmith Docs</span>
        </span>
