    <article class="day" id="day-8">
      <header class="day-head">
        <div class="day-num-big">08</div>
        <div class="day-title-block">
          <div class="day-kicker">DAY 8 · WEEK 4</div>
          <div class="day-title">Evals & Guardrails in Production</div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-toggle">+</div>
      </header>
      <div class="day-body">
        <p class="day-intro">The discipline that separates 'demo-quality' from 'shipping': systematic evaluation and runtime guardrails.</p>

        
      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Offline / online eval systems</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Offline = run against frozen test sets on every PR (cheap, repeatable). Online = score live production traffic in real time (catches drift). You need both.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://eugeneyan.com/writing/llm-evaluators/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Offline vs online evals — when to use each</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Eugene Yan</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://docs.smith.langchain.com/observability/how_to_guides/online_evaluations" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">LangSmith online eval setup</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangSmith Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Set up an online evaluator in LangSmith that runs LLM-as-judge on every production trace, scoring 'helpful' on a 1-5 scale.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Human-in-the-loop review</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Uncertain or high-stakes outputs get queued for human review before reaching the user. Common in legal, medical, financial AI products.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/concepts/human_in_the_loop/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">LangGraph Human-in-the-loop</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangGraph Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/building-effective-agents" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Designing HITL workflows</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Anthropic Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Add an 'approval' node to your graph. If the agent wants to call a 'destructive' tool (like delete or send_email), pause and wait for human confirmation.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Acute risk vs chronic drift</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Acute = single bad output that's a disaster (PII leak, medical misadvice). Block at runtime. Chronic = quality slowly decaying. Catch with online evals over time.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.anthropic.com/research/responsible-scaling-policy" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Acute vs chronic AI risk (the framework)</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Anthropic Research</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://arize.com/blog/llm-drift/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Detecting model drift in production</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Arize AI Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>List 3 acute risks for your RAG bot (e.g., leaks PII from the corpus). For each, write the runtime check that would block it.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Beyond RAG agent evals</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Agent evals look at the full trajectory: did it pick the right tools? Loop unnecessarily? Reach the right final state? Different from RAG metrics.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
