    <article class="day" id="day-11">
      <header class="day-head">
        <div class="day-num-big">11</div>
        <div class="day-title-block">
          <div class="day-kicker">DAY 11 · WEEK 6</div>
          <div class="day-title">Multi-Agent Systems</div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-toggle">+</div>
      </header>
      <div class="day-body">
        <p class="day-intro">When one agent gets too complex, split it. A supervisor routes to specialists. Powerful for research, code review, multi-domain Q&A.</p>

        
      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Multi-agent architectures</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Supervisor pattern (one router + specialists), hierarchical (supervisors of supervisors), swarm (peer-to-peer handoffs). Pick the simplest that works.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/tutorials/multi_agent/agent_supervisor/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">LangGraph multi-agent tutorial</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangGraph Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/building-effective-agents" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">When NOT to use multi-agent (sober take)</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Anthropic Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hvAPnpSfSGo" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type video">video</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Multi-agent systems with LangGraph</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangChain YouTube</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Sketch a supervisor + 3-specialist research agent on paper before writing any code. Specialists: web_researcher, code_finder, summarizer.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Subgraphs & parallel execution</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">A subgraph is a LangGraph used as a node inside a parent graph. Parallel execution lets multiple specialists run at once and aggregate results.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/how-tos/subgraph/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">LangGraph subgraphs</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangGraph Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph/how-tos/branching/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">LangGraph parallel branches (fan-out/fan-in)</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangGraph Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Implement the research agent: fan out to web_researcher and code_finder in parallel; fan in to summarizer. Time it vs sequential.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Circuit breakers & fallbacks</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">If a sub-agent or tool fails repeatedly, stop calling it for a while. Standard distributed-systems pattern; applies to flaky LLM tools and rate-limited APIs.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://martinfowler.com/bliki/CircuitBreaker.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Circuit breaker pattern explained</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Martin Fowler</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://blog.langchain.dev/resilient-agents/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Resilient agent design</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangChain Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Wrap each specialist in a circuit breaker: 2 failures in 60s → skip for 5 min. If a specialist is skipped, the supervisor falls back to a 'I don't have data on X' message.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Workflow architecture design</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Multi-agent isn't always better — it adds latency and coordination cost. Default to single-agent. Split only when one agent's prompt becomes unmaintainable.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/building-effective-agents" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Building effective AI agents — when to split</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Anthropic Engineering</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://eugeneyan.com/writing/agents/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">The case for fewer agents</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Eugene Yan</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Look at your day-11 multi-agent. Could it have been one agent with 3 tools instead? Note the tradeoff in your project README.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

        <div class="checkpoint">
          <span class="checkpoint-icon">✓</span>
          <span><strong>Checkpoint:</strong> Multi-agent adds latency and complexity — name two situations where it's still worth it, and one where it isn't.</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="day" id="day-12">
      <header class="day-head">
        <div class="day-num-big">12</div>
        <div class="day-title-block">
          <div class="day-kicker">DAY 12 · WEEK 6</div>
          <div class="day-title">Multimodal AI Engineering</div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-toggle">+</div>
      </header>
      <div class="day-body">
        <p class="day-intro">Frontier models take images, PDFs, audio, video. Multimodal RAG and document understanding are increasingly default product features.</p>

        
      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Extract data from PDFs/images</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Old way: OCR → text → process. New way: feed pages directly to a vision-language model (VLM). VLMs handle diagrams and tables that OCR mangles.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://docs.claude.com/en/docs/build-with-claude/vision" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Anthropic Vision API</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Anthropic Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://docs.unstructured.io/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Unstructured.io — extract text + images + tables from PDFs</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Unstructured</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.llamaindex.ai/blog/multimodal-rag" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">PDF extraction with VLMs vs OCR</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LlamaIndex Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Take a PDF page with a chart. Render to PNG with <code>pdf2image</code>. Send to Claude as an image. Ask: 'What's the highest value in this chart?' Compare to OCR approach.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Multimodal RAG systems</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Two patterns: (1) caption images then RAG over text, or (2) embed images and text into a shared space (CLIP-style) and retrieve directly. Pattern 1 is simpler and usually wins.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.pinecone.io/learn/multi-modal-rag/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Multimodal RAG: practical guide</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Pinecone Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YGT0JYeh1F0" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type video">video</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Multimodal RAG with LangChain + GPT-4V</span>
          <span class="resource-source">LangChain YouTube</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Build a multimodal RAG over a PDF with charts: extract text chunks AND chart images. For each chart, generate a caption with Claude Vision. Index captions alongside text. Retrieve and answer chart questions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Image + text retrieval</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">CLIP and similar models embed images and text into the same vector space. Lets you 'search images with text' or 'find related text for an image.'</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://github.com/openai/CLIP" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">OpenAI CLIP — original paper + usage</span>
          <span class="resource-source">OpenAI</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.pinecone.io/learn/series/image-search/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Building image search with CLIP</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Pinecone Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Use sentence-transformers' CLIP variant to embed 10 images. Query with the text 'a black dog'. Verify the top result is your closest dog photo.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Video understanding agents</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Sample frames at intervals (1fps), feed batches to a VLM, summarize. Useful for surveillance, sports clips, lecture transcripts, security footage analysis.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://huggingface.co/blog/video-llava" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Video QA with frame sampling + LLMs</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Hugging Face Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.twelvelabs.io/blog" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Building a video search engine</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Twelve Labs Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Take a 30-second video. Extract 1 frame per second with ffmpeg. Send all 30 frames to Claude with the question 'Summarize what happens in this video.' Note where it succeeds and fails.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

        <div class="checkpoint">
          <span class="checkpoint-icon">✓</span>
          <span><strong>Checkpoint:</strong> Why does feeding a chart's image to a VLM beat OCR-then-text in many cases?</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
    </section>

    <section class="week">
      <header class="week-header">
        <div class="week-num">07</div>
        <div class="week-info">
          <div class="week-tag">Week 7</div>
