    <article class="day" id="day-18">
      <header class="day-head">
        <div class="day-num-big">18</div>
        <div class="day-title-block">
          <div class="day-kicker">DAY 18 · WEEK 9</div>
          <div class="day-title">Fine-Tuning & Synthetic Data</div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-toggle">+</div>
      </header>
      <div class="day-body">
        <p class="day-intro">Fine-tuning a 7B model used to need a rack of A100s. In 2026, a free Colab T4 + Unsloth + QLoRA does it in an afternoon.</p>

        
      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Fine-tune vs RAG decisions</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">RAG for facts/knowledge. Fine-tune for style, format, narrow domain language, or shrinking a big-model output into a smaller, cheaper one.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.anyscale.com/blog/fine-tuning-vs-rag" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">When to fine-tune vs RAG</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Anyscale Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://huggingface.co/blog/tegridydev/fine-tuning-dev-intro-2025" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">WTF is Fine-Tuning?</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Hugging Face Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Take 3 hypothetical projects (e.g., legal-doc Q&A, brand-voice email drafting, SQL generation). For each, decide: RAG, fine-tune, or both. Justify in 2 sentences.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">LoRA & QLoRA training</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">LoRA: freeze base model, train tiny low-rank matrices on attention layers (~0.1% of params). QLoRA: same + 4-bit quantize the base. Cuts VRAM 75%.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://huggingface.co/learn/llm-course/chapter11/4" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type course">course</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Hugging Face LLM course — Chapter 11 (LoRA)</span>
          <span class="resource-source">HuggingFace</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://effloow.com/articles/llm-fine-tuning-lora-qlora-guide-2026" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Fine-Tune LLMs with LoRA and QLoRA: 2026 Guide</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Effloow</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://docs.unsloth.ai/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Unsloth quickstart (fastest LoRA)</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Unsloth Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Open a free Colab T4. Load <code>unsloth/Qwen2.5-1.5B</code> with QLoRA config (r=16, alpha=16). Verify it loads in &lt; 4GB VRAM.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Data filtering & deduplication</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Garbage in, garbage out. 500 clean examples beat 5000 noisy ones. Dedupe near-duplicates (MinHash/embedding similarity). Filter by length, language, quality score.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.philschmid.de/fine-tune-llms-in-2025" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Dataset preparation for fine-tuning</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Phil Schmid Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://lilianweng.github.io/posts/2024-02-05-human-data-quality/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Why data quality > quantity</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Lilian Weng Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Take any open dataset (e.g., OpenAssistant). Write a script to filter by length (50-500 tokens) and language (English). Drop the bottom 20% by length. Note how much shrinks.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Synthetic dataset pipelines</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">When you don't have labels: use a strong LLM to generate (input, output) pairs. Cheap, scalable, but you must filter aggressively for quality.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://huggingface.co/blog/synthetic-data-save-costs" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Generating synthetic data with LLMs</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Hugging Face Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://dspy-docs.vercel.app/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">DSPy synthetic data generation</span>
          <span class="resource-source">DSPy Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Generate 100 synthetic (question, SQL) pairs against the Chinook schema using Claude. Hand-review 10. If quality is good, fine-tune Qwen 1.5B on them and compare to base model on a held-out test set.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

        <div class="checkpoint">
          <span class="checkpoint-icon">✓</span>
          <span><strong>Checkpoint:</strong> When should you fine-tune instead of doing RAG, and what kind of task does each handle better?</span>
