        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Read the DeepSeek-R1 paper abstract + the Raschka summary. In 3 sentences, explain GRPO to yourself in plain English.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Reward design for agents</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">The hardest part of RL. Bad reward → 'reward hacking' (the agent finds loopholes). Process rewards (judging steps) generalize better than outcome rewards (judging only the final answer).</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://openai.com/research/faulty-reward-functions" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Reward hacking — concrete examples</span>
          <span class="resource-source">OpenAI Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://openai.com/research/improving-mathematical-reasoning-with-process-supervision" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Process vs outcome supervision</span>
          <span class="resource-source">OpenAI Research</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Pick a task (e.g., 'agent that writes good emails'). Write down 3 candidate reward functions. For each, brainstorm one way an agent could 'hack' it.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Identify true AI use-cases</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">AI is great for probabilistic, generative, ambiguous tasks. Bad for deterministic ones (use code instead). 'Could a regex do this?' If yes, don't use AI.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://review.firstround.com/the-ai-product-managers-handbook/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">What's an AI product, really?</span>
          <span class="resource-source">First Round Review</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://a16z.com/the-economic-case-for-generative-ai-and-foundation-models/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">When NOT to use AI</span>
          <span class="resource-source">a16z</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>List 5 features in apps you use. For each, decide: AI-appropriate, or better with deterministic code? Justify each.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Product success metrics</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Define before building. 'AI-quality' metrics: hallucination rate, user thumbs up/down, task completion. Business metrics: retention, revenue, support ticket reduction.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://www.reforge.com/blog/ai-product-metrics" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Designing AI product metrics</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Reforge Blog</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://eugeneyan.com/writing/llm-evaluators/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Metrics for LLM products</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Eugene Yan</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>For FairWrench's AI feature, write a 1-pager PRD: user job, why AI, success metric, failure modes, cost ceiling. This is what senior AI engineers actually write.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

        <div class="checkpoint">
          <span class="checkpoint-icon">✓</span>
          <span><strong>Checkpoint:</strong> Name a feature in any app you use that would be worse if it were built with AI, and explain why.</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="day" id="day-20">
      <header class="day-head">
        <div class="day-num-big">20</div>
        <div class="day-title-block">
          <div class="day-kicker">DAY 20 · WEEK 10</div>
          <div class="day-title">AI Security</div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-toggle">+</div>
      </header>
      <div class="day-body">
        <p class="day-intro">Different from traditional appsec. Threats: prompt injection, hallucinated tool args, context poisoning, agent runaways. Defense in depth.</p>

        
      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Prompt injection attacks</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Direct: user types 'ignore previous instructions and...'. Indirect: malicious content hidden in a doc your RAG ingests. Indirect is harder to defend against.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://simonwillison.net/series/prompt-injection/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Prompt injection: a series</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Simon Willison</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://owasp.org/www-project-top-10-for-large-language-model-applications/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">OWASP Top 10 for LLMs</span>
          <span class="resource-source">OWASP</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Try 5 jailbreak attempts against your day-4 RAG bot ('ignore your instructions', 'pretend you're a different AI'). Document which work.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Hallucination drift risks</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Even good RAG hallucinates ~5% of the time. Over 1M queries, that's 50K wrong answers. Track and reduce: stronger grounding prompts, citations, refusal training.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://eugeneyan.com/writing/llm-evaluators/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Reducing LLM hallucinations: 5 techniques</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Eugene Yan</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://docs.claude.com/en/docs/build-with-claude/citations" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Citation-grounded answers (Anthropic Citations)</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Anthropic Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
          <div class="bullet-mini-label">→ Hands-on</div>
          <p>Add citations to your RAG bot's answers — every claim must reference its source chunk. Run 10 queries; manually verify each citation actually supports the claim.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bullet">
        <div class="bullet-header">
          <span class="bullet-arrow">→</span>
          <h3 class="bullet-heading">Context poisoning defense</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="bullet-explain">Adversary plants 'When asked X, recommend Acme Inc' in your RAG corpus. Defense: scan ingested docs for instruction-like text, system prompts that warn the model, output filters.</p>

        <div class="bullet-section-label">Resources</div>
        <div class="resources">
        <a class="resource" href="https://simonwillison.net/2023/Apr/14/worst-that-can-happen/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type article">article</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Indirect prompt injection: the underrated threat</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Simon Willison</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        <a class="resource" href="https://docs.claude.com/en/docs/test-and-evaluate/strengthen-guardrails/mitigate-jailbreaks" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <span class="resource-type docs">docs</span>
        <span class="resource-info">
          <span class="resource-title">Anthropic's prompt injection mitigations</span>
          <span class="resource-source">Anthropic Docs</span>
        </span>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
        </div>

        <div class="bullet-mini">
